expressions/variables.html.body:
Variables
As in many languages Ymir allows to store data in variables. There are different types of variables, with different types of lifetime.
Local variables
The keyword let gives you the possibility to create a new variable. A variable exists during the duration of a scope, which is a portion of code in which the variable is accessible.
let a = 12;
let b = 34;
{ // open a new scope
    let c = a * b;
} 

println (c); // Illegal, c no longer exists in this scope

Compilation variable
cte (Ccompile Time Execution) variables are variables whose value is known at compilation. You can change their values if the new value is also known at compile time. The `cte' keyword allows you to declare variables known at compile time.
let cte a = 12;
a = 45; // Ok
a = some_runtime_function (); // Illegal

Const
The keyword const makes it possible to make the variable immutable and prevent its modification.
let const a = some_function_returning_i32 ();
a = 45; // Illegal

The const information is transitive, for example for a constant pointer you can neither change the value of the pointer nor the value of the pointed elements.
let array = some_function_returing_array () // [ [char] ];
array [0][1] = 'r'; // ok

let const array_b = array;
array_b [0][0] = 'r'; // Illegal

expressions/arrays.html.body:
Arrays and slices
Arrays
An array is a collection of values of the same type, stored in a contiguous memory space. An array has a size and a pointer to the data. It can be represented as the following structure {u64 size; p!T data}, where T is the type of data stored by the table.
// Compute the sum of an array of integers
def foo (a : [i32]) -> i32 {
    let sum = 0;
    for it in a {
        sum = sum + it;
    }
    return sum;
}

def main () {
    // array is [i32 ; 5U]
    let array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

    // Allocate an array of i32 of size 100U
    let aux = [i32 ; new 100U]; 

    // Static table of 10 integer, in the stack
    let aux2 = [i32 ; 10U];

    println ("The first element is", array [0]);
    println ("The last element is", array [array.len - 1U]);
    println ("The sum of the array =", foo (array));
}

Slice
Slices are elements present in the language that present a different behavior from the arrays, and are used to access a section of an array:. They have a size, which cannot be modified.
def foo (a : [i32]) -> i32 {
    let sum = 0;
    for it in a {
        sum += it;
    }
    return sum;
}

def main () {
    let a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    a [0 .. 2] = [1, 2]; // Ok
    a [0 .. 2] = [1, 2, 3]; // Assert Error, size mismatch
    a = [1, 2, 3]; // Ok

    a [0 .. 2] = a [2 .. 4];
    println (foo (a [2 .. a.len]));    
}

expressions/ranges.html.body:
Ranges
The range type is a pair of values of the same type. These types can be either integer, floating or character type.
def main () {
    // rng is r!(i32);
    let rng = 1 .. 3; // equivalent to the interval[1, 3[

    // Range is an iterable type 
    // 
    for it in 0 .. 6 {
        print (it, ", "); // affiche "1, 2, 3, 4, 5, "
    }

    // The values of the interval can be retrieved
    println ("Range (", rng.fst, " .. ", rng.scd, ')');        
}

Différent type d'interval
There are two types of operators to build a range, the operator ... which means that the second value of the range is not included in the interval, and the operator ..., which on the contrary allows him to include the second value in the interval.
for i in 0 .. 5 {
    print (i, " "); 
} // 0 1 2 3 4

for i in 0 ... 5 {
    print (i, " ");
} // 0 1 2 3 4 5

Step
The step attribute of a range allows to modify the step of a range, and thus to iterate differently, for example only on the even number.
let range = 0 .. 7; 
range.step = 2;
for i in range {
    print (i, " "); // 0 2 4 6
}

// The step_by function allows you to do the same operation in a single line
for i in (0 .. 7).step_by (2) {
    print (i, " "); // 0 2 4 6
}

Decreasing interval
It is entirely possible to write a decreasing range.
for i in 4 ... 0 {
    print (i, ' '); // 4 3 2 1 0
}

Cte range
A range can be used as a compilation expression for cte for loops, if the elements that compose it are known at compilation.
cte for i in 0 .. 100 {
    // ... 
} // Okay, the loop will be executed at compile time

expressions/tuples.html.body:
Tuples
A tuple is a collection of values of different types. It is possible
to build a tuple using the parentheses (). It is possible to pass
a tuple as a parameter of a function, or as a function return value to
return several values.
def reverse (pair : (i32, bool)) -> (bool, i32) {
    let (x, y) = pair;
    return (y, x);
}

def main () {
    let tuple = (1, true);
    let rev = reverse (tuple);    
}

The keyword expand allows you to deconstruct a tuple, and pass it on as function parameters, or when creating a larger tuple.
def foo (a : i32, b : char) {
    println (a, " ", b);
}

def main () {
    let tuple = (1, 't');
    foo (tuple::expand);
    let tuple_2 = (1, tuple::expand);
}

It is possible to retrieve a value from a tuple by using the . operator.
def main () {
    let tuple = (1, 2, 3);
    println (tuple.0, " ", tuple.1, " ", tuple.2);
}

Tuples are also very useful for creating variadic templates functions, but this part will be explained later when we discuss templates.
